				<div id="post-237" class="post-237 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized" > 

				

					<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://skeeping.com/north-carolinas-shameless-guvnah/" title="Permalink to North Carolina&#8217;s Shameless Guv&#8217;nah" rel="bookmark">North Carolina&#8217;s Shameless Guv&#8217;nah</a></h2>
<div class="entry-meta"><span class="meta-prep meta-prep-entry-date"></span><span class="entry-date"><abbr class="published" title="2013-11-06T01:35:55+0000">November 6, 2013</abbr></span></div><!-- .entry-meta -->
     				
					<div class="entry-content">
					
						<p><span style="font-size: 18px;">If you live in North Carolina and and watch or listen to or read the news, chances are good that you have heard of the antics of our governer, Pat McCrory, and his involvment in the state's Dept of Health and Human Services. 100 of NC's department of Social Services use a computer system called NCFAST to process assistance applications.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style="font-size: 18px;">For the last 6 months, this program has failed, miserably, and at one point Pitt County Social Services had 1,000 pending applications, and families were not receiving their food stamps.</span></p>
											
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
					
					<div class="entry-utility">

						<span class="cat-links">Posted in <a href="http://skeeping.com/category/uncategorized/" title="View all posts in Uncategorized" rel="category tag">Uncategorized</a></span>

						<span class="meta-sep meta-sep-tag-links">|</span> <span class="comments-link"><a href="http://skeeping.com/north-carolinas-shameless-guvnah/#respond" title="Comment on North Carolina&#8217;s Shameless Guv&#8217;nah" rel="bookmark">Leave a comment</a></span>

					</div><!-- .entry-utility -->
					
				</div><!-- #post -->

			
				<div id="post-107" class="post-107 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-tips-tricks tag-saving-movies-dvr tag-tips-and-tricks-for-saving-money tag-tips-and-tricks-watching-tv tag-tips-on-recording-movies tag-watching-television" > 

				

					<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://skeeping.com/recording-shows-on-your-cable-dvr-box/" title="Permalink to RECORDING MORE SHOWS ON YOUR CABLE DVR BOX" rel="bookmark">RECORDING MORE SHOWS ON YOUR CABLE DVR BOX</a></h2>
<div class="entry-meta"><span class="meta-prep meta-prep-entry-date"></span><span class="entry-date"><abbr class="published" title="2012-11-28T15:19:58+0000">November 28, 2012</abbr></span></div><!-- .entry-meta -->
     				
					<div class="entry-content">
					
						<p><span style="font-family: verdana,geneva; font-size: 14px;">Do you like to record movies on your DVR )Digital Video Recorder?  Do you wish you had more room to save more movies?  Here is a neat trick that will more than DOUBLE the amount of movies, talk shows, sitcoms, etc. you can save on your DVR box:  </span></p><p><span style="font-family: verdana,geneva; font-size: 14px;">Record the show on a non-High Definition channel. I have cable, and for every High Definition channel, there is a "sister" channel that is not in high definition. For instance, I like to watch TCM movies that broadcast in High Definition on channel 215. But the non-high definition channel is channel 15. Same movies, same broadcasts, but one is in high definition and the other is not. </span></p><p><span style="font-family: verdana,geneva; font-size: 14px;"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-106" title="couch potato" src="http://skeeping.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/couch-potato.jpg" alt="watching TV" width="266" height="190" /></span></p><p><span style="font-family: verdana,geneva; font-size: 14px;">If I want to record a movie, I record the movie on channel 15, the non-High Def channel. The difference in the size of a standard broadcast and a High-Def broadcast is substantial.  This is what allows you to record so many standard shows as opposed to the High-Def shows.  The Disney channel is broadcast in High-Definition on channel 214, but the non-High definition channel is 14. Same principle - if the children want a Disney movie recorded, I record it on channel 14. The playback is not going to be as sharp as high-definition shows are, but it's a fair trade off.</span></p><p><span style="font-family: verdana,geneva; font-size: 14px;">When recording HD shows, I was able to save 8 or 9 at a time. If I record them on non-High Definition channels, I can record up to twenty at one time! Proving it always helps to think out of-the-box. The "High Def" box!</span></p>
											
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
					
					<div class="entry-utility">

						<span class="cat-links">Posted in <a href="http://skeeping.com/category/tips-tricks/" title="View all posts in tips-tricks" rel="category tag">tips-tricks</a></span>

						<span class="meta-sep meta-sep-tag-links">|</span> <span class="tag-links"> Tagged  <a href="http://skeeping.com/tag/saving-movies-dvr/" rel="tag">saving movies DVR</a>, <a href="http://skeeping.com/tag/tips-and-tricks-for-saving-money/" rel="tag">Tips and tricks for saving money</a>, <a href="http://skeeping.com/tag/tips-and-tricks-watching-tv/" rel="tag">tips and tricks watching tv</a>, <a href="http://skeeping.com/tag/tips-on-recording-movies/" rel="tag">Tips on recording movies</a>, <a href="http://skeeping.com/tag/watching-television/" rel="tag">watching television</a></span>

